Raymond of Poitou, or Raymondin, came to court Melusine and Pressyne's only condition was that he never see her on Saturdays.
Pressyne was none too pleased about them punishing her father, and cursed them to take the form of a snake (or mermaid) from the waist down every Saturday

Elynas, broke this rule when Pressyne had triplets Melusine, Melior, and Palatyne, so the four of them were forced to go to go back to Avalon. When the children, now 15, found out, they went and punished her father, trapping him in a mountain

For those who don't know the OG tale (which to be fair I didn't know about). It was prior to the 1300s about a fresh water spirit of a holy well Pressyne, marrying the King Elynas of Albany (scotland), with one condition don't see her when she bathed or had children.

So the story of Princess Caimon is loosely based off the folktale of Melusine. A fresh water spirit of a holy well who was also a daughter of the King of Alba, and her relationship with Raymondin.

TL;DR Most of Zhongli's combat lines make you realize that yes he is in fact a 6000 year old man (also please thank a-ben (cn va) and all researcher + writers + translators for Zhongli because that had to be rough to make that sound natural & make sense)

Also since it uses half of the words you would see in modern cn, it can even be difficult for even fluent speakers to understand. Hell, I'm not even 10% sure I got the other lines right as my cn experience is "I can etymology this, maybe..." & I read book/talk mandarin goo 👁️👄👁️

So the english translation is correct for all of these (more or less). Just very straight, no poetry needed. Though to be fair, classical chinese 5 BC - 2 AD and each word use has to be a single syllable word (exceptions apply), so it works

We know that Zhongli refers to himself as heaven in this context because in other elemental burst lines he says 此乃天道 which if you read it only by characters not knowing it's classical cn would mean "This is heaven's way" and 天理长驱  "Heaven urges [you to] order"

The phrase in Chinese is "天动万象/天動萬象" (Tiān dòng wànxiàng) 天 being the subject is the sky / heavenly realm (and since Zhongli is a god, is him as he rules it) / 动 is the verb meaning move / 万 means 1000/a lot + 象 means results = 万象 all things. Heaven moves all things

Before I go to bed, reminder that zhongli's line "I will have order" in the CN is actually a phrase in classical chinese in which you try to explain as much information with as little words as possible.
